The aim of these exercises is to implement functions for analyzing historical data relating to the Olympic Games. With the functions generated, weâ€™ll be able to exploit information such as the number of medals won by each athlete during their participation in the program, the nationalities most represented at the Olympic Games and much more.

Run the following command. What does the object contain?


library(rvest)
library(purrr)

list_tables &lt;-
  session("https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liste_des_m%C3%A9daill%C3%A9s_olympiques") |&gt;
  html_elements(".wikitable") |&gt;
  html_table()

The object contains a list with 6 elements containing different databases.

Weâ€™re interested in the first table. Create an object entitledÃ©data_medailles_sport_ete containing the first element of list_tables. The table is not well formatted. Delete the first column, the column names and the first row. Rename columns to c(â€œDisciplineâ€, â€œAnneesâ€, â€œEditionsâ€, â€œEpreuves_2020â€, â€œOrâ€, â€œArgentâ€, â€œBronzeâ€, â€œTotalâ€, â€œAthletes_medaillesâ€, â€œAthletes_orâ€). The â€œEditionsâ€, â€œEpreuves_2020â€, â€œOrâ€, â€œArgentâ€, â€œBronzeâ€ and â€œTotalâ€ columns will be converted into integer columns.


#CrÃ©er data_medailles_sport_ete contenant la premiÃ¨re table de la liste 

data_medailles_sport_ete &lt;- list_tables[[1]]

# Supprimer la premiÃ¨re colonne, les noms de colonnes et la premiÃ¨re ligne

